Target     (anode): 1mm thick tungsten plate on copper rod. 12-20 degree angle. Extends out, bolted to heatsink, and insulated. Grounded.
Filament (cathode): tungsten bulb, shielded with a smooth stainless steel focusing cup (like in a flashlight) connected to negative charge of filament. Battery powered.
50-100+ kV:         HV negative to the filament's negative, HV positive to the target. Higher voltage means X-rays of higher energy.

Electrons don't reflect off the target. They dive into it, and the target shoots out X-rays in all directions, even into itself.






The vacuum in your vacuum chamber is never perfect. Place a titanium sheet inside it and scratch the sheet from the outside.
Abrasive to scratch titanium sheet: a piece of vitrified ceramic wheel for bench grinders (high-purity alumina or silicon carbide stone).

Titanium sheet
Once the chamber is a vacuum, scratch the titanium sheet by moving the iron block with a strong magnet.
A fresh titanium surface reacts with O2, N2, H2, H2O, CO, and CO2 to form a thin solid layer.
This layer must be scratched off in order to expose fresh titanium again and again.
However, fresh titanium does not react with Helium, Neon, Argon, Krypton, and Xenon.
That's why the vacuum chamber if filled with O2 or N2 over and over, to purge those noble gasses.
The chamber will keep outgassing so the titanium will need to be scratched again.

